        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Yeah fixing the underlying issue seems necessary regardless. The following patch seems to prevent all flickering from #28667 and #28668.\r\n\r\n<details><summary>Patch 1 that resulted in some test failures</summary>\r\n\r\n```diff\r\ndiff --git a/src/nvim/tui/tui.c b/src/nvim/tui/tui.c\r\nindex e1bb1e55e3..ad359f4c53 100644\r\n--- a/src/nvim/tui/tui.c\r\n+++ b/src/nvim/tui/tui.c\r\n@@ -1654,6 +1654,10 @@ void tui_raw_line(TUIData *tui, Integer g, Integer linerow, Integer startcol, In\r\n \r\n static void invalidate(TUIData *tui, int top, int bot, int left, int right)\r\n {\r\n+  if (tui->is_starting) {\r\n+    return;\r\n+  }\r\n+\r\n   Rect *intersects = NULL;\r\n \r\n   for (size_t i = 0; i < kv_size(tui->invalid_regions); i++) {\r\n```\r\n\r\n</details>\r\n\r\nActually, delaying flushing of invalid regions like so is probably better\r\n```diff\r\ndiff --git a/src/nvim/tui/tui.c b/src/nvim/tui/tui.c\r\nindex e1bb1e55e3..4c87612e87 100644\r\n--- a/src/nvim/tui/tui.c\r\n+++ b/src/nvim/tui/tui.c\r\n@@ -1436,6 +1436,13 @@ void tui_flush(TUIData *tui)\r\n   }\r\n \r\n   while (kv_size(tui->invalid_regions)) {\r\n+    // We don't want to flush invalid regions during startup to avoid clearing\r\n+    // with attributes different from the visible background after startup.\r\n+    if (tui->is_starting) {\r\n+      kv_size(tui->invalid_regions) = 0;\r\n+      break;\r\n+    }\r\n+\r\n     Rect r = kv_pop(tui->invalid_regions);\r\n     assert(r.bot <= grid->height && r.right <= grid->width);\r\n```\r\n\r\nThis still makes it so that the invalid regions are cleared with the attributes that are visible to the user after startup, but avoids some test failures with patch 1 that caused invalidated regions to not be drawn at all during startup, instead keeping the terminal background color.\r\n\r\nI'm fine with this PR if this needs to be merged quick for 0.10 but I would like to hear @bfredl @zeertzjq thought's on what to do with the `ui_flush()` in `nvim__redraw()` considering my comments above.",
