        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Upon reconsideration I'm fine with it if it's necessary for 0.10(although I think #28676 also fixes the problem this PR aims to fix), but I still believe the user doesn't necessarily need to know the distinction between flushing pending updates to the UI (`ui_flush()`) and pushing pending updates to the grid (`update_screen()`). `flush` was intended as the latter, i.e. pending window updates.\r\n\r\n> This is most frequently used to redraw a range in a buffer (to replace nvim___buf_redraw_range) or to redraw cursor (to replace an FFI call to setcursor_mayforce()), neither of which expect an extra ui_flush().\r\n\r\nI'm not sure this is true, nothing `nvim__redraw()` does actually becomes visible on the screen without calling `ui_flush()`, so why shouldn't it be called implicitly? `setcursor_mayforce()` just sets a pending cursor update, `ui_call_grid_cursor_goto()` actually moves the cursor. `range` without `ui_flush()` just marks the range for redraw, so that wouldn't match the current description either.\r\n\r\nUnder the premise \"the user called `nvim__redraw()` and Nvim should call any code necessary to reflect the requested changes\" I'm not sure implicitly calling `ui_flush()` is actually harmful. I think the fact that `:redraw/status/tabline` all call `ui_flush()` is also a good indication that `nvim__redraw()` should. So I think keeping it as is or adding an explicit `flush` for `ui_flush()`(renaming the current flush to `update`) makes more sense than this PR.",
